Abstract
Executive Summary of the Results from the First Phase of the Study ‘Determinants of Success in the Context of Vulnerable Microentrepreneurs’. The full report of the survey results can be found at the following link (Spanish)

Objectives

The general objectives of this study are the following:

  • To study the determinants of success in four Latin American countries (Colombia, Panama, Peru, and the Dominican Republic) to inform the design of low-cost interventions that support the growth of the institutions’ clients. These interventions will later be tested using a Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT) design in the second phase of the study.

  • To characterize clients based on different areas: (i) demographic and socioeconomic characteristics, (ii) business practices, (iii) financial knowledge, (iv) entrepreneurial outlook, and (v) risk and loss aversion, among others.

  • To identify differences in levels and progress between clients considered successful and those not considered successful.

Sample Selection and Survey Design

For the sample design, four categories were created based on historical data from Fundación BBVA:

  • Successful (more than one loan): Client with more than one loan between 2018 and 2020, no delinquency, and whose capital increased between the first and the last loan.
  • Unsuccessful: Client with more than one loan between 2018 and 2020, who was delinquent during the period or whose capital did not grow between the first and last loan.
  • One loan: Clients with only one loan between 2018 and 2021 who were not delinquent during the study period. This category potentially refers to “lost” clients.
  • Subjective: Clients proposed by each local office, identified as successful microentrepreneurs by local staff.

Surveys were conducted in 4 Latin American countries (Colombia, Panama, Peru, and the Dominican Republic), with approximately 600 surveys per country, except in Panama, where only 400 were conducted1.

To ensure representativeness in terms of client types, representative samples were taken from the different categories (except for the subjective group, who were directly proposed by the local offices), stratified also by business area (Agricultural or Non-Agricultural). The sample was also selected to be geographically representative, covering different regions of each country.

Results

General Description

In total, 2125 surveys were conducted across all countries, as shown in the interactive map below.

  • Colombia: 524 surveys
  • Panama: 400 surveys
  • Peru: 596 surveys
  • Dominican Republic: 605 surveys

In addition, these categories were further divided based on the client’s type of activity (agricultural or non-agricultural). The following table shows the number of surveys by category:

Fieldwork was carried out between June 2022 and January 2023, with a peak in surveys conducted in October. While most of the fieldwork in the majority of countries took place between September and November, there were some variations depending on the country2.

The following section summarizes the main results based on different definitions of success. For each definition, the following results are presented:

  1. Balance table across categories: Mean and difference between groups for various variables of interest.

  2. Variable importance in prediction models: Importance level (in %) of different variables in predicting whether an observation falls into one category (e.g., successful) or another (e.g., unsuccessful).

Subjectively Successful

  • In general, clients identified as successful by each local office tend to have better credit-related variables (e.g., assets, loan amounts), both at the time of their first loan and their most recent loan with the institution.

  • Clients in this category also report better objective outcomes, such as growth in sales and number of employees.

  • These clients are more likely to use technology in their business (e.g., virtual payment methods, online presence).

  • Finally, these clients tend to be less dishonest compared to their counterparts.

Examine whether the initial amount of the first loan can generate positive feedback effects on the probability of success.

Success Score

  • We constructed a success measure based on growth between the first and last loan (ΔLoanAmtSD), asset growth (ΔAssetsSD), and surplus growth (ΔSurplusSD), all standardized at the country level.

\[SuccessScore_i = \frac{1}{3}\Delta LoanAmtSD_i + \frac{1}{3}\Delta AssetsSD_i + \frac{1}{3}\Delta SurplusSD_i\]

  • We focus on clients in the top 10% of the distribution versus the bottom 90%.

  • The most relevant variables for prediction are related to the first loan (amount, assets, and surplus), as well as repayment capacity and knowledge of their business and its competition.

  • Willingness to pay for a training course also stands out as a relevant difference between both groups.

Access to Training

Access to training tools (e.g., business practices and/or technology) could have a significant effect on the success of a business.

  • In this section, two groups are created based on the (standardized) growth of their assets. The “successful” group corresponds to clients in the top 25% of asset growth, while the “unsuccessful” group includes those in the bottom 25%.

  • Matching is performed based on baseline characteristics to obtain two balanced groups at the time of their first loan.

Ambition as a Driver of Growth

If ambition and having bigger goals play an important role, interventions focused on mindset shifts and role models could help motivate clients.

Conclusions

  • This survey allows us to characterize the institution’s clients based on different definitions of success.

  • While the results do not demonstrate causality, they help identify potential avenues for interventions that could foster client growth.

  • Interventions targeting both clients (e.g., training, increasing ambition, etc.) and branch-level practices (e.g., client selection, loan amounts) could be tested in the second phase through a randomized experiment to measure their effectiveness.
